"{\n  \"correct\": \"no\",\n  \"explanation\": \"The np.sinc function returns an array of sinc values, but the sinc function is defined as sinc(x) = sin(pi*x)/(pi*x) if x != 0, and sinc(0) = 1. When x is an integer, the sinc function will return 0 for all non-zero x. However, sinc(0) is 1. But sinc(x) for non-zero integer x is not exactly 0 due to floating point precision. So, the assertion sinc_result[1] == 0 will fail because sinc_result[1] is not exactly 0 but a very small number close to 0.\",\n  \"patch\": \"7,9c7,9\\n< assert sinc_result[0] == 1, \\\"Results not equal to one\\\"\\n< assert sinc_result[1] == 0, \\\"Results not equal to zero\\\"\\n---\\n> np.testing.assert_allclose(sinc_result[0], 1)\\n> np.testing.assert_allclose(sinc_result[1:], 0)\"\n}"